<br>
Verant's thing lately seems to be to try to make all classes equally desirable in groups.  They're obviously not yet but that seems to be what they're going for.  Of course they've overdone it.  You will probably want 1 player controlled tank in the group.  Not a warrior necessarily, just someone who can tank (warrior, sk, paladin, monk).  If you're outdoors you don't even need that.  A mage pet tanks great.  Indoors you'll probably want 1.  Once you've got your 1 tank, you'd be crazy to take another one if a mage is available.  Absolutely crazy.  So until you've got your 1 tank, a warrior might be more desirable in dungeons at least.  Once you've got either a warrior, monk, sk, or paladin in the group, then adding a mage will be infinitely better than adding any of the previous classes.  Outdoors the mage is much better right from the start, no player tank needed.  It's not even close.  A mage is going to do more than double the damage of that player tank.  I'm always amused by the logic when people say &quot;Class X deals dmg and class Y takes dmg, therefore they are balanced&quot;.  It's far too narrow a view of balancing.  If a rogue dealt 5 times the damage of a warrior, should that be considered balanced? No!  They currently deal quite a bit more damage as they should, but there's a certain amount that makes it an equal tradeoff.  For the incredible damage a mage can kick out with their pet and nukes, the pet tanks far too well. I would argue that they are much more desirable in a group than a warrior is in most situations.  Not all players have realized that yet, but balancing changes should never, ever be done as a result of player ignorance.<br>
<br>
